02:52:45.280 --> 02:52:51.360
like at work, the tactile nature of it. It became inconvenient for sharing the notes with my team.

02:52:51.360 --> 02:52:57.360
But basically, we use a wiki type system. It's called Media Wiki, which is basically like a

02:52:57.360 --> 02:53:03.120
Wikipedia clone. Old school. Yeah, old school. So we can have pages for every guest, every topic.

02:53:03.120 --> 02:53:06.960
Oh, that's interesting. I haven't heard that. Yeah. I don't know anyone else who's using it. It

02:53:06.960 --> 02:53:13.520
works really well. It's so fast and it takes up almost no space. So it just is a really good tool.

02:53:14.240 --> 02:53:19.920
When my team, when we book a guest and they have notes from the publicist, they'll put it in there

02:53:19.920 --> 02:53:25.120
and then I can access it. So I'm basically working off of notes rather than a script. I'll pull any

02:53:25.120 --> 02:53:34.000
audio-visual stuff that I want so that that's available. And it's really a very seamless,

02:53:34.000 --> 02:53:37.280
you know, we're doing this every day, four days a week. And so we have it down to a well-oiled

02:53:37.280 --> 02:53:44.800
machine. Where do you get ideas from? Everywhere. I have a bunch of subreddits that I follow that I

02:53:44.800 --> 02:53:50.800
think are talking about interesting things. I have a curated list for which I still use Twitter,

02:53:50.800 --> 02:53:55.680
and it is very good for this. It's a curated private list of journalists that I think are

02:53:55.680 --> 02:54:02.400
doing interesting work. So I'll see what's there. Look at the sort of standard news reporting,

02:54:02.400 --> 02:54:10.240
wire services, AP and Reuters. Glance at what? Everything from Drudge to CNN to whoever is

02:54:10.240 --> 02:54:17.200
covering that day. Look at Google News. How do you try to fact check stuff on your show?

02:54:17.280 --> 02:54:22.240
So like is there sources or is there a process? I always try to get to a primary source first

02:54:22.240 --> 02:54:28.720
and foremost for the facts of the story. And then I'll use other tools for background research.

02:54:28.720 --> 02:54:36.880
Oftentimes Wikipedia's footnotes, I find to be useful tools. Chat GPT is a good one. You really

02:54:36.880 --> 02:54:41.920
have to fact check it, but it'll give you ideas of where to do the fact checking, which I think is

02:54:41.920 --> 02:54:45.680
fantastic. Sometimes it gives me information that's flat out wrong. And when you ask for the source,

02:54:45.680 --> 02:54:50.880
it's like, oh, yeah, that actually is not real, which is, hey, it's part of the process.

02:54:52.320 --> 02:54:56.320
And then when there's like an expertise type of thing, if it's a breaking legal matter,

02:54:56.320 --> 02:55:00.800
I'll just call like a friend who's a lawyer or call a friend who's a doctor or something like that.

02:55:01.440 --> 02:55:06.880
If it lends itself to that. Let me ask you about the nature of truth. Do you think it's

02:55:06.880 --> 02:55:11.760
becoming more and more difficult to know what is true and will become continuously,

02:55:12.480 --> 02:55:15.280
continue to get more difficult, especially with GPT?

02:55:16.000 --> 02:55:23.360
I think the big difficulty is in getting people to agree as to what is a statement of fact

02:55:23.360 --> 02:55:29.360
and what is a statement of opinion. I think once we can do that, reasonable people can more or

02:55:29.360 --> 02:55:34.880
less agree on how to get to the truth. Or if we can't get to it, at least figure out how we would

02:55:34.880 --> 02:55:38.720
if the information were available. But the bigger challenge I'm having is

02:55:39.680 --> 02:55:44.640
someone will call in with an opinion, but say they want to talk about fact.

02:55:45.440 --> 02:55:50.320
And I have to explain to them, you're talking about an opinion and not a fact. And this goes

02:55:50.320 --> 02:55:56.240
back to the lack of critical thinking and lack of media literacy. But that's the bigger challenge

02:55:56.240 --> 02:55:59.440
for me right now. But I mean, I think the big statements are always going to be

02:56:00.160 --> 02:56:11.520
somewhat opinions. Like was the 2020 election fair? I think any answer to that is an opinion.

02:56:12.640 --> 02:56:14.960
Disagree. If we define fair.

02:56:17.600 --> 02:56:23.840
Well, yes. So then I don't think it's possible to define fair in a way that's not several paragraphs

02:56:23.840 --> 02:56:32.000
where each sentence now has facts, right? So what do you mean by fair? Is it who can show up

02:56:32.000 --> 02:56:38.880
to vote? What was the process of how easy it is to vote? Was there actual cheating going on?

02:56:38.880 --> 02:56:42.720
And different like what is the evidence of that cheating? You have to actually get to the actual

02:56:42.720 --> 02:56:48.720
like details of a thing. High level, you know, everything is just going to be an opinion, it

02:56:48.720 --> 02:56:56.480
feels like. And you can approximate that to be like, it's a well-founded opinion. Well,

02:56:56.480 --> 02:57:01.440
most of science is an opinion, even physics is an opinion. So like, I think there's a threshold

02:57:01.440 --> 02:57:08.240
beyond which an opinion becomes like, this is a pretty reliable thing to assume for now that

02:57:08.240 --> 02:57:15.440
that's okay. So let me revise. So I think maybe better said, I think that the difficulty,

02:57:16.400 --> 02:57:23.360
I mean, the process you described is probably the right process and it's exhausting for mundane

02:57:23.360 --> 02:57:31.360
things and that causes major problems. If we were to say, is it better for the economy to have

02:57:32.080 --> 02:57:39.840
a tax rate on people making over a million dollars that's 20% or 50%? Okay. What do we mean by better

02:57:39.840 --> 02:57:45.360
for the economy? It's not an overwhelming task to decide on that. We could say, well, we'll say it's

02:57:45.360 --> 02:57:49.760
better for the economy by looking at what was the unemployment rate based on the tax rate on

02:57:49.760 --> 02:57:55.600
million, you know, people earning a million a year and what was GDP and whatever. Okay. We've

02:57:55.600 --> 02:58:02.880
agreed. This is a statement. We are now in the realm of just determining what is given the parameters

02:58:02.880 --> 02:58:09.120
that we've established. I think that that's relatively doable. The issue is with the bigger

02:58:09.120 --> 02:58:14.880
ones like you're talking about where what do we mean by a fair election and fair in whose eyes and

02:58:14.880 --> 02:58:21.200
but I am with you that it often devolves into a conversation about opinions about what is fair

02:58:22.000 --> 02:58:28.000
rather than an ascertainment of the facts. Yeah. And it feels like maybe avoiding some

02:58:28.000 --> 02:58:33.440
of these big, maybe there's some trigger words too, maybe avoiding them allows you to actually

02:58:33.440 --> 02:58:39.520
talk about the facts and through that educate yourself and learn about like whether the virus

02:58:39.520 --> 02:58:45.600
leaked from a lab or not. To me was always a super interesting question. I don't know why

02:58:45.600 --> 02:58:50.720
everybody got super touchy about it. Mostly people I know, colleagues, biologists thought

02:58:52.400 --> 02:58:58.400
it's pretty good likelihood that it leaked from a lab given everything. They just didn't the evidence

02:58:58.400 --> 02:59:03.760
is not there for a either one. And so like you should be able to just openly talk about it.

02:59:03.760 --> 02:59:08.960
Unless you're in the high political office where there could be geopolitical consequences to your

02:59:08.960 --> 02:59:12.240
statements. But in general, it's an interesting question. You should be able to talk about it.

02:59:12.240 --> 02:59:16.160
But there's no, first of all, there's not many facts around there, unfortunately.

02:59:17.680 --> 02:59:21.920
And a lot of very conclusive statements about especially in the early days were just opinions.

02:59:22.480 --> 02:59:28.000
And so you have to the idea of what is true and not becomes a little

02:59:28.880 --> 02:59:31.840
even mentioning the word truth in that context. It feels

02:59:31.840 --> 02:59:39.440
divisive. Yeah, I completely agree with you, which is strange. You think it shouldn't.

02:59:39.440 --> 02:59:45.120
One of the really good opening questions that I've had work to my advantage when talking with

02:59:45.120 --> 02:59:50.400
people who I know disagree with me about a contentious topic is how do you think we would

02:59:50.400 --> 02:59:58.400
figure out X? And it often gets people thinking first collaboratively. And obviously we might

02:59:58.400 --> 03:00:02.560
have very different opinions. But with something like the COVID lab leak, I think it's an interesting

03:00:02.560 --> 03:00:07.520
one. Because if you say, okay, maybe it leaked, maybe it didn't. How would we figure that out?

03:00:07.520 --> 03:00:12.240
Who would we trust to weigh in on that? What evidence would count? Now we're kind of on the

03:00:12.240 --> 03:00:18.720
same team. And then if we can establish that, then we're on a search for a capital T truth together

03:00:18.720 --> 03:00:23.200
or whatever. It's kind of pie in the sky. But in some conversations, I've actually had success with

03:00:23.760 --> 03:00:29.360
that. And then you can kind of realize if there's no amount of evidence that's going to prove

03:00:29.360 --> 03:00:34.720
a show to you that you're wrong in your current opinion, that that's probably a really bad sign

03:00:34.720 --> 03:00:38.720
for you. It's a waste. It may be a waste to pursue the conversation further at that point.

